{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5dbe025-3fa7-4681-9a62-b39d01bc7e50","content":"The working directory is empty, so there's no repo context to draw from. Here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, you can still get crash data:\n\n1. **Check Apple's built-in crash reports** — macOS automatically writes `.ips` / `.crash` files to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a report matching your process name and timestamp.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Core files land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. Then analyze with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./your-app\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to catch the crash live**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./your-app\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) bt        # backtrace\n   (lldb) process save-core dump.core\n   ```\n\n4. **SIP note** — System Integrity Protection can suppress core dumps for some paths. If `/cores/` is empty after a crash, check SIP status with `csrutil status` and ensure the binary isn't in a SIP-protected location.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"73160aab-2c63-4108-b96b-86a5ec1cb613","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"7640:E52A2:19AE1EE:1D43AEF:69FE92FE"},"id":"a1d26f5a-d9f2-4a11-887b-29be9f9741b7","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:51:03.113Z","parentId":"2bb5b34d-72df-4424-a494-b1cb8e50eeae"}
